04327nam a22006735i 9780226480954DE-B159720191022022751.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||191022s2017    ilu    fo  d z      eng d  a97802264809547 a10.7208/97802264809542doi  a(DE-B1597)524408  a(OCoLC)995778202  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ailucUS-IL 4aLC1023b.H37 2018 7aEDU0000002bisacsh04a370.1122231 aHarpham, Geoffrey Galt, eauthor.10aWhat Do You Think, Mr. Ramirez? :bThe American Revolution in Education /cGeoffrey Galt Harpham. 1aChicago : bUniversity of Chicago Press, c[2017] 4cÂ©2017  a1 online resource (224 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPreface -- tI. The American Revolution in Education -- tII. Rights of the Pryvat Spyrit: From Dissent to Interpretation -- tIII. The Peculiar Opportunities of English -- tPostscript: In Praise of Depth -- tNotes -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aGeoffrey Galt Harpham's book takes its title from a telling anecdote. A few years ago Harpham met a Cuban immigrant on a college campus, who told of arriving, penniless and undocumented, in the 1960s and eventually earning a GED and making his way to a community college. In a literature course one day, the professor asked him, "Mr. Ramirez, what do you think?" The question, said Ramirez, changed his life because "it was the first time anyone had asked me that." Realizing that his opinion had value set him on a course that led to his becoming a distinguished professor.             That, says Harpham, was the midcentury promise of American education, the deep current of commitment and aspiration that undergirded the educational system that was built in the postwar years, and is under extended assault today. The United States was founded, he argues, on the idea that interpreting its foundational documents was the highest calling of opinion, and for a brief moment at midcentury, the country turned to English teachers as the people best positioned to train students to thrive as interpreters-which is to say as citizens of a democracy. Tracing the roots of that belief in the humanities through American history, Harpham builds a strong case that, even in very different contemporary circumstances, the emphasis on social and cultural knowledge that animated the midcentury university is a resource that we can, and should, draw on today.    aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 22. Okt 2019) 0aEducationzUnited StatesxPhilosophy. 0aEducation, HigherzUnited States. 0aEducation, HumanisticzUnited StatesxHistory. 0aEducation, HumanisticzUnited States. 0aEnglish literature - Study and teaching (Higher) - United States - History - 20th century. 0aEnglish literaturexStudy and teaching (Higher)zUnited StatesxHistoryy20th century. 0aEnglish literaturexStudy and teaching (Higher)zUnited States. 4aAmerica. 4aEnglish. 4ademocracy. 4aeducation. 4ageneral education. 4aintended meaning. 4ainterpretation. 4aliberal education. 4aliterary study. 4aopinion. 7aEDUCATION / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press eBook Package 2016-2018z978311063537940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226480954423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780226480954.jpg  a978-3-11-063537-9  University of Chicago Press eBook Package 2016-2018c2016d2018  aGBV-deGruyter-alles